data.content:
## What Breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider allowed synchronous operations via an explicit **sync-over-async opt-in** (e.g., `CosmosOptionsExtension.EnableSyncOverAsync`). In .NET 11, **that opt-in is removed entirely**. Every synchronous LINQ call against the Cosmos provider now throws `InvalidOperationException` at runtime.

**Affected methods in your code:**

| Sync (breaks) | Async (replacement) |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `ToListAsync()` |
| `First(...)` | `FirstAsync(...)` |
| `Count()` | `CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `SaveChangesAsync()` |

## The Fix

Convert the repository to async throughout:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- This is a **runtime** break — code compiles fine but throws at execution.
- `async/await` must propagate up the call chain to controllers/handlers.
- `Add()` stays synchronous — it only tracks in-memory; the actual I/O is `SaveChangesAsync()`.
- Remove any `EnableSyncOverAsync` configuration — it no longer exists.
